WHEREAS, CNS Esmeralda, a steel-hulled, four-masted barquentine, serves as
Chile's sail training ship and is often called "La Dama Blanca", or "The White Lady"; the
ship is capable of both engine and wind propulsion and historically acts as a diplomatic tool
and symbol of national pride; and
WHEREAS, the BAP Unión (BEV-161) is a four-masted, steel-hulled barque and
the largest sail training vessel in Latin America; the ship was commissioned by the Peruvian
Navy in 2016 and built by Servicios Industriales de la Marina in Callao, Peru; it serves as
a floating ambassador and training platform for naval cadets and honors the legacy of the
nineteenth-century corvette Unión; and
WHEREAS, the ARC Gloria is a striking three-masted steel barque built in Spain
and commissioned by the Colombian Navy in 1968; the ship functions as both the
Colombian Navy's flagship and its principal sail-training vessel, and it embodies Colombia's
maritime traditions while charting courses as a sailing ambassador around the world; and
WHEREAS, the ROU Capitán Miranda is a three-masted schooner of the Uruguayan
Navy that was originally launched in 1930 as a hydrographic research vessel; the ship was
converted into a sail-training ship in 1978 and now serves to train young officers in
seamanship and leadership and participates in international tall ship events; and
WHEREAS, GLADAN is one of two sail training ships operated by the Swedish
Navy and was built in 1947 to replace earlier training ships; the ship is designed as a square
topsail schooner in the traditional Baltic pilot style and serves as a platform for cadets to
gain hands-on experience in seamanship, navigation, and leadership while voyaging across
the world; and
WHEREAS, the HNLMS Friesland (P842) is a Holland-class offshore patrol vessel
that is operated by the Royal Netherlands Navy and was commissioned on January 22, 2013;
the ship is named after the Dutch province of Friesland and serves as a modern multi-role
platform for maritime security and law enforcement; and
WHEREAS, ARA Libertad is a three hundred forty-foot, three-masted, steel-hulled
tall ship based in Buenos Aires that was built in 1963; the ship is one of the world's largest
and fastest tall ships, serves as a training vessel for the Argentine Navy, and has sailed over
eight hundred thousand nautical miles and visited five hundred ports in more than sixty
countries; and
